\[f(\bm{u})\geqslant f(\bm{v}^{*}),\ \ \text{for all}\ \bm{u}\in B(\bm{v}^{*}; \delta)\cap\hat{\Omega}.\] (A.31)

The fact \(\bm{v}^{*}\in\hat{\Omega}\) gives \(\iota_{\hat{\Omega}}(\bm{v}^{*})=0\). Then (A.31) implies that \(\hat{F}(\bm{u})\geqslant\hat{F}(\bm{v}^{*})\) for all \(\bm{u}\in B(\bm{v}^{*};\delta)\), that is, \(\bm{v}^{*}\) is a local minimizer of \(\hat{F}\). Now it follows from Lemma 24 that \(\bm{v}^{*}\) is also a global minimizer of \(\hat{F}\). The strict convexity of \(\hat{F}\) implies the uniqueness of its global minimizer.

We next prove item \((ii)\). From item \((i)\) in this theorem and item \((ii)\) in Theorem 5, we see that \(\bm{v}^{*}\in\hat{\Omega}\) is a globally optimal solution of model (3.10) and \(\bm{v}^{*}\neq\bm{0}_{N}\). Then we are able to prove that \(\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}^{*}=(\bm{v}^{*})^{\top}\bm{Q}_{\bm{v}}\bm{v}^{*}>0\). We omit this proof here since it is very similar to the proof of Lemma 8. Now we have \(\bm{v}^{*}=\frac{\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}^{*}}{(\bm{v}^{*})^{\top}\bm{Q}_{\bm{v}} \bm{v}^{*}}\bm{v}^{*}\). For any \(\bm{v}\in\hat{\Omega}\) such that \(\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}>0\), we let \(\bm{u}:=\frac{\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}}{\bm{Q}_{\bm{v}}\bm{v}}\bm{v}\). Then \(\bm{u}\in\hat{\Omega}\) and \(\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{u}>0\). Hence

\[-\frac{1}{2}\frac{(\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}^{*})^{2}}{(\bm{v}^{*})^{\top}\bm{Q}_{ \bm{v}}\bm{v}^{*}}=\frac{1}{2}(\bm{v}^{*})^{\top}\bm{Q}_{\bm{\epsilon}}\bm{v}^ {*}-\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}^{*}\leqslant\frac{1}{2}\bm{u}^{\top}\bm{Q}_{\bm{ \epsilon}}\bm{u}-\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{u}=-\frac{1}{2}\frac{(\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v})^{2 }}{\bm{v}^{\top}\bm{Q}_{\bm{\epsilon}}\bm{v}},\]

which implies that

\[\frac{\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}^{*}}{\sqrt{(\bm{v}^{*})^{\top}\bm{Q}_{\bm{\epsilon} }\bm{v}^{*}}}\geqslant\frac{\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}}{\sqrt{\bm{v}^{\top}\bm{Q}_{ \bm{\epsilon}}\bm{v}}},\ \ \text{for all}\ \bm{v}\in\hat{\Omega}.\]

Since \(\bm{v}^{*}\in\hat{\Omega}\) and \(\bm{v}^{*}\neq\bm{0}_{N}\), by the definition of \(\hat{\Omega}_{1}\), we see that \(\bm{w}^{*}\in\hat{\Omega}_{1}\). Note that \(\hat{\Omega}_{1}\subset\hat{\Omega}\). For all \(\bm{w}\in\hat{\Omega}_{1}\),

\[\frac{\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{w}}{\sqrt{\bm{w}^{\top}\bm{Q}_{\bm{\epsilon}}\bm{w}}} \leqslant\frac{\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{v}^{*}}{\sqrt{(\bm{v}^{*})^{\top}\bm{Q}_{\bm{ \epsilon}}\bm{v}^{*}}}=\frac{\bm{p}^{\top}\bm{w}^{*}}{\sqrt{(\bm{w}^{*})^{\top }\bm{Q}_{\bm{\epsilon}}\bm{w}^{*}}},\]

which implies that \(\bm{w}^{*}\) is a globally optimal solution of model \(\max\limits_{\bm{w}\in\hat{\Omega}_{1}}S(\bm{w})\).

Lastly, we prove item \((iii)\). Note that \(w^{*}_{j}>0\) for all \(j\in J^{\bm{v}^{*}}_{\text{pos}}\). Let \(w^{*}_{\text{min-pos}}:=\min\limits_{j\in J^{\bm{v}^{*}}_{\text{pos}}}\{w^{*}_{j}\}\), \(\delta:=\frac{1}{3}w^{*}_{\text{min-pos}}\), and let \(\bm{w}\) be any vector in \(B(\bm{w}^{*};\delta)\cap\Omega_{1}\). Then \(w_{j}\geqslant 2\delta>0\) for \(j\in J^{\bm{v}^{*}}_{\text{pos}}\), and \(|w_{j}|\leqslant\delta\) for \(j\in\mathbb{N}_{N}\backslash J^{\bm{v}^{*}}_{\text{pos}}\). Since \(\bm{w}\in\Omega_{1}\) and \(m_{\bm{v}^{*}}=m\), we conclude that \(w_{j}=0\) for \(j\in\mathbb{N}_{N}\backslash J^{\bm{v}^{*}}_{\text{pos}}\), which implies that \(\bm{w}\in\hat{\Omega}_{1}\). It has been shown that \(\bm{w}^{*}\) is an optimal solution of model \(\max\limits_{\bm{w}\in\hat{\Omega}_{1}}S(\bm{w})\).

Therefore, \(S(\bm{w})\leqslant S(\bm{w}^{*})\) for all \(\bm{w}\in B(\bm{w}^{*};\delta)\cap\Omega_{1}\), that is, \(\bm{w}^{*}\) is a locally optimal solution of model (3.3). This completes the proof. 

### Proof of Theorem 7

Proof.: According to Theorem 1 and item \((i)\) in Theorem 2, to prove the desired result, it suffices to show that

\[\bm{v}^{*}=\operatorname{prox}_{\iota_{\Omega}}\left(\bm{v}^{*}-\frac{1}{\epsilon }\nabla f(\bm{v}^{*})\right).\] (A.32)

From the proof of Theorem 5, we know that (3.8) holds. According to the computation of \(\operatorname{prox}_{\epsilon_{\Omega}}\) in Proposition 3, to guarantee the validity of (3.8), we have \(\nabla_{i}f(\bm{v}^{*})=0\) for all \(i\in\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\). Otherwise, there exists some \(i_{0}\in\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\) such that \(v^{*}_{i_{0}}\neq v^{*}_{i_{0}}-\alpha\nabla_{i_{0}}f(\bm{v}^{*})\), which together with Proposition 3 implies that \(\bm{v}^{*}\neq\operatorname{prox}_{\iota_{\Omega}}(v^{*}-\alpha\nabla f(\bm{v}^{ *}))\), a contradiction to (3.8).

Suppose that \(m_{\bm{v}^{*}}<m\). Then we have \(\nabla_{i}f(\bm{v}^{*})\geqslant 0\) for all \(i\in\mathbb{N}_{N}\backslash\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\). Otherwise, there exists some \(i_{1}\in\mathbb{N}_{N}\backslash\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\) such that \(v^{*}_{i_{1}}-\alpha\nabla_{i_{1}}f(\bm{v}^{*})>0\). Note that \(m_{\bm{v}^{*}}<m\). The operation of \(\operatorname{prox}_{{}_{\alpha_{0}}}\) will preserve the positive value \(v_{i}^{*}-\alpha\nabla_{i_{1}}f(\bm{v}^{*})\) instead of truncating it as 0, which violates (3.8). In this case, we now have \(v_{i}^{*}-\frac{1}{\epsilon}\nabla_{i}f(\bm{v}^{*})=v_{i}^{*}\) for \(i\in\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\) and \(v_{i}^{*}-\frac{1}{\epsilon}\nabla_{i}f(\bm{v}^{*})\leqslant 0\) for \(i\in\mathbb{N}_{N}\backslash\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\), which imply that (A.32) holds.

Suppose that item \((ii)\) holds. Let \(\delta:=\min\{v_{i}^{*}|i\in\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\}>0\). For \(i\in\mathbb{N}_{N}\backslash\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\), since \(\frac{1}{\epsilon}\nabla_{i}f(\bm{v}^{*})>-\delta\) and \(v_{i}=0\), we have \(v_{i}^{*}-\frac{1}{\epsilon}\nabla_{i}f(\bm{v}^{*})<\delta\). Note that \(m_{\bm{v}^{*}}=m\). The operation of \(\operatorname{prox}_{{}_{\alpha_{0}}}\) makes \(v_{i}^{*}-\frac{1}{\epsilon}\nabla_{i}f(\bm{v}^{*})=v_{i}^{*}\) for \(i\in\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\) and \(v_{i}^{*}-\frac{1}{\epsilon}\nabla_{i}f(\bm{v}^{*})=0\) for \(i\in\mathbb{N}_{N}\backslash\operatorname{supp}(\bm{v}^{*})\), that is, (A.32) holds. This completes the proof. 

### Validation of PGA's Global Optimality Through Simulation Experiments

To test the validation of PGA's global optimality, we conduct a set of simulation experiments by considering model (3.7), where \(\bm{Q}_{\epsilon}:=\bm{Q}^{\top}\bm{Q}+\epsilon\bm{I}\). The iterative scheme of PGA for solving this model is given by (3.9) with \(\alpha=\frac{0.99}{\|\bm{Q}\|_{2}}\).

In the simulation experiments, we set \(\bm{\Sigma}\in\mathbb{R}^{10\times 10}\) by \(\Sigma_{ij}:=0.5^{|i-j|}\), and randomly generate a matrix \(\bm{Q}\in\mathbb{R}^{50\times 10}\) from the multivariate normal distribution, with mean vector \(\bm{0}_{10}\) and covariance matrix \(\bm{\Sigma}\). We set \(\bm{p}\) as a random vector with components that are randomly generated numbers in the range \([-10,10]\), and casually set \(\epsilon=0.001\) and the sparsity \(m=3\).

The direct exhaustive approach enumerates all possible support set configurations, totaling \(C_{10}^{3}=120\) cases. In each case, we solve a 3-dimension quadratic programming problem. By comparing the optimal solutions corresponding to these 120 cases, we obtain the exact globally optimal solution of model (3.7). After that, we can evaluate the optimality of PGA's convergence.

For each experiment, we performed 500 iterations of PGA. To ensure the robustness of our findings, we used three different initializations: \(\bm{0}_{N}\), \(\bm{1}_{N}/N\) and \(\bm{1}_{N}\). We repeated the experiments \(10^{4}\) times for each initialization, with different \(\bm{Q}\) and \(\bm{p}\) in each run. We found that in over 7,200 of the \(10^{4}\) trials, for any of the three initializations, both the normalized error of the iterative sequence \(\|\bm{v}^{(k)}-\bm{v}^{*}\|_{2}/\|\bm{v}^{*}\|_{2}\) and the normalized error of the function value \(|f(\bm{v}^{(k)})-f(\bm{v}^{*})|/|f(\bm{v}^{*})|\) were smaller than \(10^{-10}\). Here \(\bm{v}^{*}\) denotes the globally optimal solution, and \(\bm{v}^{(k)}\) represents the iterative sequence at the \(k\)-th iteration of PGA. We show the plots of \(\|\bm{v}^{(k)}-\bm{v}^{*}\|_{2}/\|\bm{v}^{*}\|_{2}\) and \(|f(\bm{v}^{(k)})-f(\bm{v}^{*})|/|f(\bm{v}^{*})|\) in the following Figure 1, and show in Table 4 these two normalized errors obtained at 500 iterations of PGA in ten simulation experiments.

From the simulation experiments, we conclude that the proposed PGA has a high probability (over 72%) of directly converging to a globally optimal solution of model (3.7). This finding is consistent with the sufficient conditions for global optimality in Theorem 7.

